    149 CHAPTER 4 Frequency Response Analysis Main Index Forces in rigid elements are requested by MPCFORCE output requests. MPC forces are output in the displacement coordinates systems of the points to which they are attached. The force at the upper grid point of the RBAR element is in the same coordinate system as that of the connected grid point, which was modeled to be the same as that of the CBUSH element. The force transmitted to the body point can be determined from the MPC force at the other point of the RBAR element. This force is in the basic coordinate system, the coordinate system of the connected body point because this happens to be the CD system (blank, or 0) specified for that grid point. MPC (and SPC) forces include effects from all of the matrices used to compute the dynamic analysis solutions, including all forms of stiffness, viscous damping, ge and g damping, and mass. This instrumentation technique applies not only to the BUSH element in transient analysis, but is applicable to all elements in linear analysis. For direct frequency response analysis , the element force in the BUSH element matches the MPC force to many digits of accuracy. For the modal frequency response analysis, the two force outputs match within a few percent, with the differences resulting from modal truncation effects. For the transient response analysis , the MPC forces provide the only method for output of the force acting on the element. Performance Analysis The important parameters in the incremental costs associated with adding frequency-dependent elements to a model are as follows: The ratio of frequency dependent elements to other elements. The types of frequency dependent damping requested. Whether frequency dependent elements intersect constrained DOFs. Whether modal or direct analysis is chosen. Whether there are omitted DOFs. The use of frequency-dependent elements in modal analysis blocks the DDRMM method of data recovery, and the mode displacement method is used instead. The modal matrices used for solution will be coupled, not diagonal, as a consequence of the incremental impedances due to frequency-dependent effects. In direct analysis, there is no DDRMM method of data recovery and the addition of the incremental matrices for frequency-dependent elements does not affect the cost of computation of the solution module itself significantly. There are added costs associated with assembling and reducing the incremental impedance matrices for the solution module. Discussion of Results The modal method costs less than half of the direct method. In fact, if the DDRMM method is not blocked. If there are no damping effects, a real matrix solution can be used rather than a complex solution, and even more of the cost can be avoided. Much of the added cost due to connections of this type can be avoided by not requesting constraint-force output. GE damping is considerably more expensive than viscous damping. The approximations of the modal method are more pronounced for a large number of frequency-dependent elements, while computation costs approach direct analysis costs. These trends indicate that a direct analysis offers increased accuracy over a modal analysis at small incremental costs when the proportion of frequency-dependent

    MSC Nastran Dynamic Analysis User’s Guide Frequency -Dependent Excitation Definition150 Main Index elements is large. That modal analysis, however, retains its cost advantage over direct analysis when the proportion of frequency-dependent elements is small. Frequency -Dependent Excitation Definition An important aspect of a frequency response analysis is the definition of the loading function. In a frequency response analysis, the force must be defined as a function of frequency. Forces are defined in the same manner regardless of whether the direct or modal method is used. The following Bulk Data entries are used for the frequency -dependent load definition: The particular entry chosen for defining the dynamic loading is largely a function of user convenience for concentrated loads. Pressure and distributed loads, however, require a more complicated format if the LOADSET/LSEQ combination is required. There are two important aspects of dynamic load definition. First, the location of the loading on the structure must be defined. Since this characteristic locates the loading in space, it is called the spatial distribution of the dynamic loading. Secondly, the frequency variation in the loading is the characteristic that differentiates a dynamic load from a static load. This frequency variation is called the temporal distribution of the load. A complete dynamic loading is a product of spatial and temporal distributions. Using Table IDs and Set IDs in MSC Nastran makes it possible to apply many complicated and temporally similar loadings with a minimum of input. Combining simple loadings to create complicated loading distributions that vary in position as well as frequency is also a straightforward task. The remainder of this section describes the Bulk Data entries for frequency -dependent excitation. The description is given in terms of the coefficients that define the dynamic load. Frequency Dependent Materials in MSC Nastran Introduction The MAT1, MAT2, MAT8, MAT9, and MAT10 material entries may be frequency dependent. Also, elements properties such as shell thickness on the PSHELL or various ply data on the PCOMP or PCOMPG entries may be spatially dependent while keeping the traditional “element set” grouping of the PSHELL, PCOMP , or PCOMPG. Benefits Vibration damping is essential to the performance of a variety of advanced engineering systems. Material damping is an important contributor to the overall system damping in many applications such as spacecraft structures, integrally-bladed disks in turbomachinery and noise abatement in vehicles. Examples of such structures are laminated metal (where two thin sheets of steel or aluminum are bonded together by a thin viscoelastic frequency-dependent damping layer), laminated glass windscreens or layered/random fiber composites. Use of such laminates provide for a lighter and more efficient damping treatment. Modern composite materials offer the development of structural damping that is, however, sensitive to temperature and frequency. The mechanical properties of constituent fiber and matrix materials often exhibit significant frequency-dependency. With the use of the new MAT1F , MAT2F , MAT8F , and MAT9F entries this frequency dependency of material behavior on structural response can be expeditiously studied. Modern composites such as Carbon fiber are exceptionally light and tough and are able to be molded into complex structural shapes required for many high-end products. One of the parameters that define the properties of the material is how carbon fibers are draped onto complex parts. Often the region undergoing this draping process has been defined in the structural model by the elements in the region being referenced Field Contents SID Load Set ID. S Overall scale factor. Frequency Dependency Frequency dependency for the V2018 release is in addition to the current PBUSHT , PELAST , and PDAMPT specified via the following new entries: Case Control MFREQUENCY The C ase Control allows for Master frequencies in MODAL Frequency analysis with full matrix operations and for frequencies listed on the existing current FREQUENCY interpolated frequencies between master frequencies. Master frequencies allow for full solution vector and element data recovery. Interpolated frequencies allow only solution vector data recovery. Interpolation is either linear or log. Bulk Data PCOMPFQ GE field on PCOMP/PCOM PG MAT1F Allows material properties to be frequency dependent. MAT2F Allows anisotropic material properties to be frequency dependent. MAT8F Allows orthotropic material properties to be frequency dependent. MAT9F Allows anisotropic material properties to be frequency dependent. MAT10F Allows fluid frequency dependency. PFASTT GE field on PFAST . PARAM, NMNLFRQ Allows users to select material or property values for frequency dependent materials or properties at a desired frequency other than the “nominal” values specified on the MATi or PBUSH , PCOMP , PCOMPG , PDAMP , or PELAS entries.

    163 CHAPTER 4 Frequency Response Analysis Main Index The bulk data entries use the usual hierarchical selection. For example if a MAT2 is to be made frequency dependent then as MAT2F is supplied. Spatial Dependency: For the V2018 release spatial dependency is specified via the PDISTB and PDISTBM entries. See Bulk Data section below. See Remark 8 of PDISTB entry for supported property entries and data fields. The PDISTB allows the user to select a specific property entry such as PCOMP and then select a sub-group of elements referenced by PCOMP to have different properties that vary from the default properties listed on the PCOMP e ntry. The user specifies for a specific PDISTB referring to PCOMP the property name ( PNAME ) that is changing and then lists for each element of the group for which that property value changes the pair (EID, real value Vi) and using the expression VALUEi = SMULT* Vi + DELTA MSC Nastran replaces the referred to PNAME of that element by VALUEi. The scalar multiplier SMULT and the DELTA value are common to all elements listed on a specific PDISTB entry. For example suppose the user wishes to change the thickness of ply three for a sub group of elements listed on PCOMP . Since ply numbering can vary, for example the PCOMP entry allows the user to specify either a single ply for each continuation entry or two plies per continuation entry, the LOCNUM on the PDISTB refers to the Numerical order of Ply in PCOMP or PCOMPG . Thus to change ply thickness T3 for each of the elements listed, the user simply specifics PNAME=T and LOCNUM=3 . The PDISTBM is similar except that it allows the user to define a new material MATi to the selected elements. With the standard restriction that the changed MIDi represents a new MIDi to the input, it must be unique to all other MIDi entries. On a PDISTB, the PID referred to may not have an associated PCOMPFQ entries. A fatal message will be issued if there is such an association.SOL111 Bulk Data SUPORT requirement. SOL111 residual vector methods for viscous and structural damping have been greatly enhanced and orthogonalization techniques are employed which require the removal of free – free modes. For this reason the structure must be statically constrained with the use of SUPORT entries. A Case Control selectable SUPORT1 entry may also be used.
